ly high wages in the outsourcing sector have empowered a class of cultural emulators. These young Indians indulge in American-style shopping binges at glittering malls, party at upscale nightclubs, and arrange romantic trysts at exurban cafés. But while the high-tech outsourcing industry is a matter of considerable pride for India, global corporations view the industry as a low-cost, often low-skill sector. Workers use the digital tools of the information economy not to complete technologically innovative tasks but to perform grunt work and rote customer service. Long hours and the graveyard shift lead to health problems and social estrangement. Surveillance is tight, management is overweening, and workers are caught in a cycle of hope and disappointment. Through lively ethnographic detail and subtle analysis of interviews with workers, managers, and employers, Nadeem demonstrates the culturally transformative power of globalization and its effects on the lives of the individuals at its edges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aBusinessxIndia. 0aBusiness. 0aCall center agentszIndiaxSocial conditions. 0aContracting outxIndia. 0aContracting outxSocial aspectszIndia. 0aContracting outzIndia. 0aCulture diffusionxIndia. 0aCulture diffusionzIndia. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectsxIndia. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszIndia. 0aHigh technology services industrieszIndiaxEmployeesxSocial conditions. 0aInternational business enterprisesxEmployeesxSocial conditions. 0aOffshore outsourcingxIndia. 0aOffshore outsourcingzIndia. 0aSocial changexIndia. 0aSocial changezIndia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBombay.  aExport-Processing Zones.  aIndia.  aIndian workers.  aTyler Pfeifer.  aUnited States.  aaccents.  aattrition.  abusiness cosmopolitanism.